reviewee_report: CT HEAD WO IV CONTRAST (STROKE)  INDICATION: Neuro deficit, acute, stroke suspected. Lightheadedness/dizziness for one day, woke up in the middle of the night and experienced room spinning sensation with neck stiffness.  COMPARISON: MRI brain <<DATE>>  TECHNIQUE: CT images were obtained from the skull base to the vertex without intravenous contrast. Coronal and sagittal multiplanar reformatted images were provided.  FINDINGS:  There is no intracranial hemorrhage, edema, mass, mass effect or midline shift. There is no evidence of acute major vascular distribution infarct. The ventricles and sulci are symmetric and normal in size. The basal cisterns are patent.   The paranasal sinuses and mastoid air cells are clear. The visualized orbits and osseous structures are unremarkable.  IMPRESSION:   No acute intracranial abnormality.  Please note that additional contemporaneous imaging with CTA head and neck (+ or - CT perfusion imaging) is also being performed, which can better evaluate for ischemic stroke that may not be apparent on these images. Please refer to those images and report for final determination regarding imaging findings of ischemia.   <<HOSPITAL>> Radiology Notify System Classification: Routine.  Report initiated by:  <<HCW>>

reviewee_report: MRI BRAIN W WO IV CONTRAST performed on <<DATE>> 11:54 AM  INDICATION: Metastatic disease evaluation. Metastatic lung cancer.  COMPARISON: MRI brain <<DATE>>, MRI face <<DATE>>  TECHNIQUE: Multiplanar MR of the brain was performed before and after administration of contrast intravenously.    IV CONTRAST:  14 mL gadoterate meglumine (DOTAREM) 0.5 mmol/mL (376.9 mg/mL) injection  FINDINGS:  There is no acute infarct.  There is no intracranial hemorrhage. Redemonstrated punctate focus of parenchymal enhancement in the right precentral gyrus (series 16,001 image 160), unchanged compared to most recent MRI of <<DATE>> although less prominent as compared to prior MRI of <<DATE>>.  No new intracranial enhancing lesion.  When allowing for differences in imaging technique compared to the MRI face from <<DATE>>, slight interval decrease in size and degree of enhancement and restricted diffusion within osseous right mandibular ramus of partially imaged mildly enhancing mildly diffusion restricting marrow replacing lesion. This mass again involves the medial aspect of the right masseter muscle, with continued involvement of the right trigeminal mandibular nerve and its branches including the inferior alveolar nerve.  There is no mass effect, edema, or midline shift.  The ventricles are symmetric and normal in size.   Redemonstrated scattered nonenhancing periventricular and subcortical white matter T2/FLAIR hyperintensities, nonspecific but likely reflects mild chronic microangiopathic changes.  No extra-axial collection is seen.  The pituitary, pineal gland, craniocervical junction, and upper cervical spinal cord are normal in configuration.  The visualized orbits are unremarkable. Mild scattered mucosal thickening in the bilateral ethmoid sinuses, right greater than left, as well as left greater than right maxillary sinus. The mastoid air cells are clear.  IMPRESSION: 1. Stable punctate focus of enhancement in right precentral gyrus compared to <<DATE>>, although less prominent as compared to <<DATE>>. No new enhancing intracranial lesions.  2. Slight interval decrease in size and degree of enhancement and restricted diffusion within the partially imaged right mandibular ramus metastatic lesion. Redemonstrated similar involvement of medial aspect of right masseter and right trigeminal mandibular nerve and its branches including the inferior alveolar nerve.       <<HOSPITAL>> Radiology Notify System Classification: Routine.  Report initiated by:  <<HCW>>
